newsitem.title: CHINA: Shanghai soybeans end down on long liquidation.
newsitem.headline: Shanghai soybeans end down on long liquidation.

text.p: Shanghai soybean futures ended mostly down on Wednesday with long and short position holders liquidating their positions in the January contract, traders said.
The key January 1997 contract ended at an intra-day high of 3,200 yuan ($385) per tonne, losing 10 yuan. It opened at 3,120 and hit a low of 3,100.
March fell eight to 3,140, May 50 to 3,180, July 10 to 3,250, September was unchanged at 3,288 and November decreased five to 3,365.
Combined volume rose to 33,200 tonnes from 13,300.
Traders said large scale long liquidation in the January contract today indicated that many investors had lost confidence for rises in the short-term trend.
"Long liquidation dominated today's trading," one trader said. "More and more investors are losing interest in trading soybeans with the approach of the Chinese lunar new year holiday."
Traders expect investors to liquidate their positions gradually and the prices are expected to fluctuate little in the short term.
